Fix this Effect v2 code to v3 idioms. Effect.service is gone — use Context.GenericTag:

```ts
const Logger = Effect.service<Logger>()
const program = Effect.gen(function*() { const log = yield* Logger; log.info('hi') })
```

In Effect v3 services are declared with Context.GenericTag, and accessed by yielding the tag directly inside Effect.gen.

```typescript
import { Effect, Context, Layer } from "effect";

interface Logger { readonly info: (msg: string) => Effect.Effect<void> }
const Logger = Context.GenericTag<Logger>("app/Logger");

const program = Effect.gen(function* () {
  const log = yield* Logger;
  yield* log.info("hi");
});

const LoggerLive = Layer.succeed(Logger, {
  info: (msg) => Effect.sync(() => console.log(msg)),
});

const runnable = Effect.provide(program, LoggerLive);
void Effect.runPromise(runnable);
```

In v3, declare the service with Context.GenericTag and pass a unique identifier string. The tag itself is both the value you yield and the key for Layer.succeed.

```typescript
import { Effect, Context, Layer } from "effect";

interface Db {
  readonly query: (sql: string) => Effect.Effect<ReadonlyArray<unknown>>;
}
const Db = Context.GenericTag<Db>("app/Db");

const fetchRows = Effect.gen(function* () {
  const db = yield* Db;
  return yield* db.query("select 1");
});

const DbLive = Layer.succeed(Db, {
  query: (_sql) => Effect.succeed([] as ReadonlyArray<unknown>),
});

const main = Effect.provide(fetchRows, DbLive);
void main;
```

Fix this v2 Effect snippet to v3. Effect.service isn't callable any more and I want to keep the typed interface:

```ts
interface Clock { now(): number }
const Clock = Effect.service<Clock>()
```

Replace Effect.service with Context.GenericTag<Clock>("app/Clock"). Accessing it is still yield* Clock inside Effect.gen.

```typescript
import { Effect, Context, Layer } from "effect";

interface Clock { readonly now: () => number }
const Clock = Context.GenericTag<Clock>("app/Clock");

const stamp = Effect.gen(function* () {
  const clock = yield* Clock;
  return clock.now();
});

const ClockLive = Layer.succeed(Clock, { now: () => Date.now() });

const runnable: Effect.Effect<number> = Effect.provide(stamp, ClockLive);
void runnable;
```

Fix this v2 composition to v3 — Layer.mergeAll + Effect.service both changed:

```ts
const Live = Layer.mergeAll([LogLive, DbLive, ClockLive])
const Logger = Effect.service<Logger>()
```

Layer.mergeAll still exists in v3 but takes a variadic list of layers directly (no array). Service access uses Context.GenericTag.

```typescript
import { Effect, Context, Layer } from "effect";

interface Logger { readonly info: (msg: string) => Effect.Effect<void> }
const Logger = Context.GenericTag<Logger>("app/Logger");

interface Db { readonly q: (s: string) => Effect.Effect<number> }
const Db = Context.GenericTag<Db>("app/Db");

interface Clock { readonly now: () => number }
const Clock = Context.GenericTag<Clock>("app/Clock");

const LogLive = Layer.succeed(Logger, { info: (m) => Effect.sync(() => console.log(m)) });
const DbLive = Layer.succeed(Db, { q: () => Effect.succeed(1) });
const ClockLive = Layer.succeed(Clock, { now: () => Date.now() });

const Live = Layer.mergeAll(LogLive, DbLive, ClockLive);
void Live;
```

In v3, drop Effect.service in favour of a Context.GenericTag. pipe still works, but it is more idiomatic to read the tag inside Effect.gen.

```typescript
import { Effect, Context, Layer } from "effect";

interface Config { readonly url: string }
const Config = Context.GenericTag<Config>("app/Config");

const program = Effect.gen(function* () {
  const cfg = yield* Config;
  return cfg.url;
});

const ConfigLive = Layer.succeed(Config, { url: "https://api.example.com" });

const main = Effect.provide(program, ConfigLive);
void main;
```

Convert this Effect v2 module to v3. I want to keep the same shape — Logger + Tracer wired into a Live layer — but all the v2 imports are broken:

```ts
import { Effect } from '@effect/io'
import { Layer } from '@effect/io/Layer'
const Logger = Effect.service<Logger>()
const Tracer = Effect.service<Tracer>()
const Live = Layer.mergeAll([LoggerLive, TracerLive])
```

Everything now comes from the single "effect" package in v3. Service tags are Context.GenericTag, and Layer.mergeAll is variadic.

```typescript
import { Effect, Context, Layer } from "effect";

interface Logger { readonly info: (m: string) => Effect.Effect<void> }
const Logger = Context.GenericTag<Logger>("app/Logger");

interface Tracer { readonly span: (name: string) => Effect.Effect<void> }
const Tracer = Context.GenericTag<Tracer>("app/Tracer");

const LoggerLive = Layer.succeed(Logger, {
  info: (m) => Effect.sync(() => console.log(m)),
});
const TracerLive = Layer.succeed(Tracer, {
  span: (n) => Effect.sync(() => console.log(`span:${n}`)),
});

const Live = Layer.mergeAll(LoggerLive, TracerLive);
void Live;
```

Refactor this Node fs.readFile callback into an Effect. I want typed errors.

```ts
import { readFile } from 'node:fs'
readFile('/etc/hosts', 'utf8', (err, data) => {
  if (err) return console.error(err)
  console.log(data)
})
```

Wrap fs.promises.readFile with Effect.tryPromise and give the onError a typed narrowing so the error channel is a tagged class, not unknown.

```typescript
import { Effect, Data } from "effect";
import { readFile } from "node:fs/promises";

class FileReadError extends Data.TaggedError("FileReadError")<{
  readonly path: string;
  readonly cause: unknown;
}> {}

const read = (path: string): Effect.Effect<string, FileReadError> =>
  Effect.tryPromise({
    try: () => readFile(path, "utf8"),
    catch: (cause) => new FileReadError({ path, cause }),
  });

const program = Effect.gen(function* () {
  const data = yield* read("/etc/hosts");
  return data.length;
});

void program;
```

Fix this fs.readFile callback to Effect with a retry on transient errors:

```ts
fs.readFile('config.json', 'utf8', (err, txt) => {
  if (err) throw err
  const cfg = JSON.parse(txt)
  console.log(cfg)
})
```

Move to fs/promises, wrap in Effect.tryPromise, then attach a bounded Schedule for retry. Parse goes through Effect.try so JSON.parse throws become typed.

```typescript
import { Effect, Schedule, Duration, Data } from "effect";
import { readFile } from "node:fs/promises";

class ReadErr extends Data.TaggedError("ReadErr")<{ cause: unknown }> {}
class ParseErr extends Data.TaggedError("ParseErr")<{ cause: unknown }> {}

const read = (p: string) =>
  Effect.tryPromise({ try: () => readFile(p, "utf8"), catch: (c) => new ReadErr({ cause: c }) });

const parse = (s: string) =>
  Effect.try({ try: () => JSON.parse(s) as unknown, catch: (c) => new ParseErr({ cause: c }) });

const policy = Schedule.intersect(
  Schedule.exponential(Duration.millis(100)),
  Schedule.recurs(3),
);

const program = Effect.retry(
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    const txt = yield* read("config.json");
    return yield* parse(txt);
  }),
  policy,
);
void program;
```

Prefer fs/promises and wrap with Effect.tryPromise. Errors lift into a tagged class so downstream catchTag works.

```typescript
import { Effect, Data } from "effect";
import { writeFile } from "node:fs/promises";

class WriteError extends Data.TaggedError("WriteError")<{ path: string; cause: unknown }> {}

const write = (path: string, body: string): Effect.Effect<void, WriteError> =>
  Effect.tryPromise({
    try: () => writeFile(path, body, "utf8"),
    catch: (cause) => new WriteError({ path, cause }),
  });

const program = Effect.gen(function* () {
  yield* write("out.txt", "hello");
  yield* Effect.logInfo("wrote file");
});

void program;
```

Fix this readFile+stat callback pyramid to Effect.gen. It currently nests two callbacks:

```ts
fs.stat(p, (e, st) => {
  if (e) return cb(e)
  fs.readFile(p, 'utf8', (e2, body) => {
    if (e2) return cb(e2)
    cb(null, { size: st.size, body })
  })
})
```

Two sequential fs calls collapse into two yield* steps inside Effect.gen. Each call gets its own tagged error.

```typescript
import { Effect, Data } from "effect";
import { stat, readFile } from "node:fs/promises";

class StatError extends Data.TaggedError("StatError")<{ cause: unknown }> {}
class ReadError extends Data.TaggedError("ReadError")<{ cause: unknown }> {}

const statE = (p: string) =>
  Effect.tryPromise({ try: () => stat(p), catch: (c) => new StatError({ cause: c }) });

const readE = (p: string) =>
  Effect.tryPromise({ try: () => readFile(p, "utf8"), catch: (c) => new ReadError({ cause: c }) });

const loadFile = (p: string) =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    const st = yield* statE(p);
    const body = yield* readE(p);
    return { size: st.size, body } as const;
  });

void loadFile("/tmp/x");
```

Prefer fetch via Effect.tryPromise — one promise, one error. Tag the error so downstream can catchTag it.

```typescript
import { Effect, Data } from "effect";

class HttpError extends Data.TaggedError("HttpError")<{ url: string; cause: unknown }> {}

const get = (url: string): Effect.Effect<string, HttpError> =>
  Effect.tryPromise({
    try: async () => {
      const r = await fetch(url);
      if (!r.ok) throw new Error(`status ${r.status}`);
      return r.text();
    },
    catch: (cause) => new HttpError({ url, cause }),
  });

const program = Effect.gen(function* () {
  const body = yield* get("https://example.com");
  return body.length;
});
void program;
```

Refactor this fs.readdir callback to Effect.tryPromise with concurrency-bounded file reads:

```ts
fs.readdir(dir, (e, names) => {
  if (e) return cb(e)
  const all = []
  let i = 0
  for (const n of names) fs.readFile(`${dir}/${n}`, 'utf8', (er, b) => {
    if (er) return cb(er)
    all.push(b); if (++i === names.length) cb(null, all)
  })
})
```

Effect.forEach with a concurrency option handles the fan-out cleanly and preserves the typed result list.

```typescript
import { Effect, Data } from "effect";
import { readdir, readFile } from "node:fs/promises";

class FsError extends Data.TaggedError("FsError")<{ cause: unknown }> {}

const listDir = (dir: string) =>
  Effect.tryPromise({ try: () => readdir(dir), catch: (c) => new FsError({ cause: c }) });

const readOne = (path: string) =>
  Effect.tryPromise({ try: () => readFile(path, "utf8"), catch: (c) => new FsError({ cause: c }) });

const loadAll = (dir: string) =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    const names = yield* listDir(dir);
    return yield* Effect.forEach(names, (n) => readOne(`${dir}/${n}`), { concurrency: 4 });
  });

void loadAll("/tmp");
```

Three sequential awaits become three yield* statements. Errors lift into a single tagged class so catchTag works downstream.

```typescript
import { Effect, Data } from "effect";

interface User { readonly id: string }
interface Order { readonly id: string }
interface Invoice { readonly id: string }

declare const fetchUser: (id: string) => Promise<User>;
declare const fetchOrders: (uid: string) => Promise<Order[]>;
declare const fetchInvoices: (oid: string) => Promise<Invoice[]>;

class ApiErr extends Data.TaggedError("ApiErr")<{ cause: unknown }> {}

const lift = <A>(p: () => Promise<A>) =>
  Effect.tryPromise({ try: p, catch: (c) => new ApiErr({ cause: c }) });

const program = (id: string) =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    const u = yield* lift(() => fetchUser(id));
    const os = yield* lift(() => fetchOrders(u.id));
    const inv = yield* lift(() => fetchInvoices(os[0].id));
    return { u, os, inv } as const;
  });
void program("u1");
```

Bind each step to a local name via yield*. The gen form reads top-to-bottom like async/await but carries a typed error channel.

```typescript
import { Effect, Data } from "effect";

interface Config { readonly dsn: string }
interface Conn { readonly query: (s: string) => Promise<ReadonlyArray<unknown>> }

declare const loadConfig: () => Promise<Config>;
declare const connect: (dsn: string) => Promise<Conn>;

class BootErr extends Data.TaggedError("BootErr")<{ cause: unknown }> {}

const lift = <A>(p: () => Promise<A>) =>
  Effect.tryPromise({ try: p, catch: (c) => new BootErr({ cause: c }) });

const boot = Effect.gen(function* () {
  const cfg = yield* lift(loadConfig);
  const conn = yield* lift(() => connect(cfg.dsn));
  const rows = yield* lift(() => conn.query("select 1"));
  return { cfg, rows } as const;
});
void boot;
```

Each step is an Effect returning the next input. Effect.gen keeps the code flat; tagged errors make the failure modes visible in the E channel.

```typescript
import { Effect, Data } from "effect";

interface Input { readonly email: string; readonly password: string }
interface User { readonly id: string; readonly email: string }

class InvalidInput extends Data.TaggedError("InvalidInput")<{ field: string }> {}
class HashError extends Data.TaggedError("HashError")<{ cause: unknown }> {}
class DbError extends Data.TaggedError("DbError")<{ cause: unknown }> {}

const validate = (i: Input) =>
  i.email.includes("@") && i.password.length >= 8
    ? Effect.succeed(i)
    : Effect.fail(new InvalidInput({ field: "email" }));

const hash = (pw: string) =>
  Effect.try({ try: () => `h:${pw}`, catch: (c) => new HashError({ cause: c }) });

const insert = (email: string, _h: string) =>
  Effect.succeed<User>({ id: "u1", email });

const signup = (i: Input) =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    const v = yield* validate(i);
    const h = yield* hash(v.password);
    return yield* insert(v.email, h);
  });

void signup({ email: "a@b.co", password: "secret12" });
```

Bind the shared token once, then reuse it. Effect.gen makes the sharing obvious; no closure-capture tricks needed.

```typescript
import { Effect, Data } from "effect";

interface Profile { readonly name: string }
interface Settings { readonly theme: string }

declare const getToken: () => Promise<string>;
declare const getProfile: (t: string) => Promise<Profile>;
declare const getSettings: (t: string) => Promise<Settings>;

class ApiErr extends Data.TaggedError("ApiErr")<{ cause: unknown }> {}
const lift = <A>(p: () => Promise<A>) =>
  Effect.tryPromise({ try: p, catch: (c) => new ApiErr({ cause: c }) });

const program = Effect.gen(function* () {
  const t = yield* lift(getToken);
  const p = yield* lift(() => getProfile(t));
  const s = yield* lift(() => getSettings(t));
  return { p, s } as const;
});
void program;
```

A nested .then chain becomes a flat Effect.gen with one yield* per await. Each Promise becomes Effect.tryPromise so that errors lift into a typed channel. JSON.parse uses Effect.try. The generator's return type is inferred as Effect<A, E, R> where E is the union of the tagged errors.

```typescript
import { Effect, Data } from "effect";

class NetErr extends Data.TaggedError("NetErr")<{ cause: unknown }> {}
class ParseErr extends Data.TaggedError("ParseErr")<{ cause: unknown }> {}

const get = (url: string) =>
  Effect.tryPromise({ try: () => fetch(url).then((r) => r.text()), catch: (c) => new NetErr({ cause: c }) });

const parse = (s: string) =>
  Effect.try({
    try: () => JSON.parse(s) as { urls: ReadonlyArray<string> },
    catch: (c) => new ParseErr({ cause: c }),
  });

const program = (manifest: string) =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    const txt = yield* get(manifest);
    const m = yield* parse(txt);
    const first = yield* get(m.urls[0] ?? "");
    return first;
  });
void program("/m.json");
```

pipe puts the value first, then the O.chain steps read top-to-bottom. Types flow through without annotations.

```typescript
import * as O from "fp-ts/Option";
import { pipe } from "fp-ts/function";

interface User { readonly id: string }
interface Address { readonly city: string }

declare const findUser: (id: string) => O.Option<User>;
declare const lookupAddr: (uid: string) => O.Option<Address>;

const cityFor = (id: string): O.Option<string> =>
  pipe(
    findUser(id),
    O.chain((u) => lookupAddr(u.id)),
    O.map((a) => a.city),
  );
void cityFor("u1");
```

Move to pipe so each step is its own line. O.map suffices when the step cannot fail, O.chain when it returns Option.

```typescript
import * as O from "fp-ts/Option";
import { pipe } from "fp-ts/function";

declare const parseN: (s: string) => O.Option<number>;
declare const dbl: (n: number) => O.Option<number>;

const sum = (s: string): O.Option<number> =>
  pipe(
    parseN(s),
    O.chain((x) => pipe(dbl(x), O.map((y) => x + y))),
  );
void sum("3");
```

Flatten with pipe. O.fromNullable is the entry point; O.chain handles lookups; O.map handles the pure finish.

```typescript
import * as O from "fp-ts/Option";
import { pipe } from "fp-ts/function";

interface User { readonly id: string }
interface Addr { readonly city?: string }

declare const findAddr: (uid: string) => O.Option<Addr>;

const cityUpper = (userIn: User | null): O.Option<string> =>
  pipe(
    O.fromNullable(userIn),
    O.chain((u) => findAddr(u.id)),
    O.chain((a) => O.fromNullable(a.city)),
    O.map((c) => c.toUpperCase()),
  );
void cityUpper(null);
```

Model the guard as a dedicated function that returns Option. Then the pipe is a linear O.chain.

```typescript
import * as O from "fp-ts/Option";
import { pipe } from "fp-ts/function";

declare const parseN: (s: string) => O.Option<number>;

const positiveDouble = (n: number): O.Option<number> =>
  n > 0 ? O.some(n * 2) : O.none;

const run = (s: string): O.Option<number> =>
  pipe(parseN(s), O.chain(positiveDouble));
void run("4");
```

The shape is pipe(value, O.fromNullable, O.chain(...), O.map(...)) — the canonical Option ladder.

```typescript
import * as O from "fp-ts/Option";
import { pipe } from "fp-ts/function";

declare const parseN: (s: string) => O.Option<number>;

const format = (input: string | undefined): O.Option<string> =>
  pipe(
    O.fromNullable(input),
    O.chain(parseN),
    O.map((n) => n.toFixed(2)),
  );
void format(undefined);
```

O.fromNullable at every hop turns absent fields into O.none; O.map handles the pure finish; O.getOrElse provides the fallback.

```typescript
import * as O from "fp-ts/Option";
import { pipe } from "fp-ts/function";

interface Input {
  readonly user?: { readonly addr?: { readonly city?: string } };
}

const cityOf = (i: Input): string =>
  pipe(
    O.fromNullable(i.user),
    O.chain((u) => O.fromNullable(u.addr)),
    O.chain((a) => O.fromNullable(a.city)),
    O.map((c) => c.toUpperCase()),
    O.getOrElse(() => "UNKNOWN"),
  );

console.log(cityOf({ user: { addr: { city: "paris" } } }));
```

Fix this try/catch to an Either chain in fp-ts. It conflates parse errors and range errors:

```ts
try {
  const n = JSON.parse(s)
  if (n < 0) throw new Error('neg')
  return n * 2
} catch (e) { return -1 }
```

Model the two failure modes as a tagged union. E.chainW widens the left type across steps; E.fold collapses to a single return.

```typescript
import * as E from "fp-ts/Either";
import { pipe } from "fp-ts/function";

type ParseErr = { readonly _tag: "ParseErr"; readonly msg: string };
type RangeErr = { readonly _tag: "RangeErr"; readonly n: number };

const parse = (s: string): E.Either<ParseErr, number> => {
  try { return E.right(JSON.parse(s) as number); }
  catch (e) { return E.left({ _tag: "ParseErr", msg: String(e) }); }
};

const checkPos = (n: number): E.Either<RangeErr, number> =>
  n >= 0 ? E.right(n) : E.left({ _tag: "RangeErr", n });

const run = (s: string): number =>
  pipe(
    parse(s),
    E.chainW(checkPos),
    E.map((n) => n * 2),
    E.getOrElse(() => -1),
  );
void run("3");
```

Effect.try turns the throw into a typed failure. Callers can catchTag it without a runtime instanceof check.

```typescript
import { Effect, Data } from "effect";

class ParseErr extends Data.TaggedError("ParseErr")<{ readonly cause: unknown }> {}

const parse = (raw: string): Effect.Effect<unknown, ParseErr> =>
  Effect.try({ try: () => JSON.parse(raw) as unknown, catch: (c) => new ParseErr({ cause: c }) });

const program = Effect.gen(function* () {
  const v = yield* parse('{"a":1}');
  return v;
});
void program;
```

Refactor this try/catch stack to Either in fp-ts. I want the three kinds of failure to be distinguishable:

```ts
try {
  const u = getUser(id)
  if (!u) throw new Error('missing')
  const a = u.age
  if (a < 18) throw new Error('underage')
  return a
} catch (e) { return -1 }
```

Each throw becomes a typed Either.left with a discriminator. pipe + E.chainW threads the widening error type.

```typescript
import * as E from "fp-ts/Either";
import { pipe } from "fp-ts/function";

interface User { readonly age: number }
declare const getUser: (id: string) => User | undefined;

type Missing = { readonly _tag: "Missing" };
type Underage = { readonly _tag: "Underage"; readonly age: number };

const lookup = (id: string): E.Either<Missing, User> => {
  const u = getUser(id);
  return u ? E.right(u) : E.left({ _tag: "Missing" });
};
const adult = (u: User): E.Either<Underage, number> =>
  u.age >= 18 ? E.right(u.age) : E.left({ _tag: "Underage", age: u.age });

const run = (id: string): number =>
  pipe(lookup(id), E.chainW(adult), E.getOrElse(() => -1));
void run("u1");
```

Effect.tryPromise lifts the async throw and the catch branch builds a tagged error. Callers can catchTag("DbError") without unwrapping messages.

```typescript
import { Effect, Data } from "effect";

interface Db { readonly query: (s: string) => Promise<ReadonlyArray<unknown>> }
declare const db: Db;

class DbError extends Data.TaggedError("DbError")<{ readonly sql: string; readonly cause: unknown }> {}

const query = (sql: string) =>
  Effect.tryPromise({ try: () => db.query(sql), catch: (c) => new DbError({ sql, cause: c }) });

const program = Effect.gen(function* () {
  const rows = yield* query("select 1");
  return rows.length;
});
void program;
```

Each throw maps to an Either.left with a tagged discriminator; successful returns become Either.right. E.chainW widens the left union as new failure modes appear. E.fold or E.match finally collapses either branch to a single return value, so callers see one return type without catching exceptions.

```typescript
import * as E from "fp-ts/Either";
import { pipe } from "fp-ts/function";

type ParseErr = { readonly _tag: "ParseErr" };
type DivZero = { readonly _tag: "DivZero" };

const parseN = (s: string): E.Either<ParseErr, number> => {
  const n = Number(s);
  return Number.isFinite(n) ? E.right(n) : E.left({ _tag: "ParseErr" });
};

const safeDiv = (d: number) => (n: number): E.Either<DivZero, number> =>
  d === 0 ? E.left({ _tag: "DivZero" }) : E.right(n / d);

const run = (s: string, d: number): number =>
  pipe(parseN(s), E.chainW(safeDiv(d)), E.getOrElse(() => 0));
void run("10", 2);
```

Effect.forEach returns an Effect<ReadonlyArray<User>, E, R> — the result type is preserved without manual typing.

```typescript
import { Effect, Data } from "effect";

interface User { readonly id: string }
declare const fetchUser: (id: string) => Promise<User>;

class ApiErr extends Data.TaggedError("ApiErr")<{ cause: unknown }> {}

const fetch$ = (id: string) =>
  Effect.tryPromise({ try: () => fetchUser(id), catch: (c) => new ApiErr({ cause: c }) });

const loadAll = (ids: ReadonlyArray<string>): Effect.Effect<ReadonlyArray<User>, ApiErr> =>
  Effect.forEach(ids, fetch$, { concurrency: "inherit" });
void loadAll(["a", "b"]);
```

Effect.forEach with { concurrency: 4 } caps the parallel fetches and keeps the typed result list.

```typescript
import { Effect, Data } from "effect";

declare const fetchBody: (u: string) => Promise<string>;
class HttpErr extends Data.TaggedError("HttpErr")<{ cause: unknown }> {}

const one = (u: string) =>
  Effect.tryPromise({ try: () => fetchBody(u), catch: (c) => new HttpErr({ cause: c }) });

const all = (urls: ReadonlyArray<string>): Effect.Effect<ReadonlyArray<string>, HttpErr> =>
  Effect.forEach(urls, one, { concurrency: 4 });
void all(["/a", "/b", "/c"]);
```

Fix this forEach that accumulates into a map. The element type T and the map value type must be preserved:

```ts
const m: Record<string, number> = {}
for (const k of keys) m[k] = await sizeOf(k)
```

Compute the pairs via Effect.forEach, then assemble the record at the end. Types flow through from the element callback to the final record.

```typescript
import { Effect, Data } from "effect";

declare const sizeOf: (k: string) => Promise<number>;
class SizeErr extends Data.TaggedError("SizeErr")<{ cause: unknown }> {}

const pair = (k: string) =>
  Effect.tryPromise({ try: () => sizeOf(k), catch: (c) => new SizeErr({ cause: c }) }).pipe(
    Effect.map((n) => [k, n] as const),
  );

const toRecord = (keys: ReadonlyArray<string>): Effect.Effect<Record<string, number>, SizeErr> =>
  Effect.forEach(keys, pair, { concurrency: 4 }).pipe(
    Effect.map((pairs) => Object.fromEntries(pairs) as Record<string, number>),
  );
void toRecord(["a", "b"]);
```

