Fix this async/await chain to a TaskEither pipeline. Two promises in sequence:

```ts
async function boot() {
  const cfg = await loadCfg()
  const conn = await connect(cfg.dsn)
  return conn
}
```

Lift each step with TE.tryCatch, then TE.chain sequences them. The error channel is widened via TE.chainW if the two errors differ.

```typescript
import * as TE from "fp-ts/TaskEither";
import { pipe } from "fp-ts/function";

interface Cfg { readonly dsn: string }
interface Conn { readonly id: string }

declare const loadCfg: () => Promise<Cfg>;
declare const connect: (dsn: string) => Promise<Conn>;

type CfgErr = { readonly _tag: "CfgErr"; readonly cause: unknown };
type ConnErr = { readonly _tag: "ConnErr"; readonly cause: unknown };

const boot = (): TE.TaskEither<CfgErr | ConnErr, Conn> =>
  pipe(
    TE.tryCatch(loadCfg, (u): CfgErr => ({ _tag: "CfgErr", cause: u })),
    TE.chainW((cfg) => TE.tryCatch(() => connect(cfg.dsn), (u): ConnErr => ({ _tag: "ConnErr", cause: u }))),
  );
void boot;
```

Fix this async/await to a TaskEither.tryCatch form. It throws either a network or parse error:

```ts
async function fetchJson(u: string) {
  const r = await fetch(u)
  return JSON.parse(await r.text())
}
```

Split the two failure modes: the network await and the JSON.parse throw. TE.tryCatch is used for each, chained via pipe.

```typescript
import * as TE from "fp-ts/TaskEither";
import { pipe } from "fp-ts/function";

type NetErr = { readonly _tag: "NetErr"; readonly cause: unknown };
type ParseErr = { readonly _tag: "ParseErr"; readonly cause: unknown };

const body = (u: string): TE.TaskEither<NetErr, string> =>
  TE.tryCatch(async () => (await fetch(u)).text(), (c): NetErr => ({ _tag: "NetErr", cause: c }));

const parse = (s: string): TE.TaskEither<ParseErr, unknown> =>
  TE.tryCatch(async () => JSON.parse(s) as unknown, (c): ParseErr => ({ _tag: "ParseErr", cause: c }));

const fetchJson = (u: string): TE.TaskEither<NetErr | ParseErr, unknown> =>
  pipe(body(u), TE.chainW(parse));
void fetchJson("/a");
```

Each step is its own TE. TE.fromEither lifts a pure validation; TE.map handles the pure finish. The error is a tagged singleton union.

```typescript
import * as TE from "fp-ts/TaskEither";
import * as E from "fp-ts/Either";
import { pipe } from "fp-ts/function";

type Err = { readonly _tag: "NaNErr"; readonly input: string };

const parse = (s: string): E.Either<Err, number> => {
  const n = Number(s);
  return Number.isFinite(n) ? E.right(n) : E.left({ _tag: "NaNErr", input: s });
};

const run = (s: string): TE.TaskEither<Err, number> =>
  pipe(TE.fromEither(parse(s)), TE.map((n) => n * 2));
void run("42");
```

Declare an HttpClient tag, inject it via Layer, and the program reads it from context. The try/catch disappears because tryPromise handles the throw.

```typescript
import { Effect, Context, Layer, Data } from "effect";

class HttpErr extends Data.TaggedError("HttpErr")<{ cause: unknown }> {}

interface HttpClient { readonly get: (u: string) => Effect.Effect<string, HttpErr> }
const HttpClient = Context.GenericTag<HttpClient>("app/HttpClient");

const HttpClientLive = Layer.succeed(HttpClient, {
  get: (u) => Effect.tryPromise({
    try: () => fetch(u).then((r) => r.text()),
    catch: (c) => new HttpErr({ cause: c }),
  }),
});

const program = Effect.gen(function* () {
  const http = yield* HttpClient;
  return yield* http.get("https://example.com");
});

const main = Effect.provide(program, HttpClientLive);
void main;
```

Effect.forEach's signature is (items: Iterable<A>, f: (a: A) => Effect<B, E, R>, opts?) => Effect<ReadonlyArray<B>, E, R>. The element type A is inferred from the iterable, the mapper's B becomes the array element type, and the result preserves input ordering even when concurrency is set. Because the signature is polymorphic, TypeScript refuses mismatched element types at compile time — no manual casts needed.

```typescript
import { Effect, Data } from "effect";

interface Item { readonly id: string }
interface Out { readonly id: string; readonly size: number }

declare const size: (i: Item) => Promise<number>;
class SizeErr extends Data.TaggedError("SizeErr")<{ cause: unknown }> {}

const one = (i: Item): Effect.Effect<Out, SizeErr> =>
  Effect.tryPromise({ try: () => size(i), catch: (c) => new SizeErr({ cause: c }) }).pipe(
    Effect.map((n) => ({ id: i.id, size: n })),
  );

const all = (xs: ReadonlyArray<Item>): Effect.Effect<ReadonlyArray<Out>, SizeErr> =>
  Effect.forEach(xs, one, { concurrency: 4 });
void all;
```

One Context.GenericTag for the HttpClient, one composed Schedule, one Effect.retry. Everything is typed; no any.

```typescript
import { Effect, Context, Layer, Schedule, Duration, Data } from "effect";

class HttpErr extends Data.TaggedError("HttpErr")<{ cause: unknown }> {}

interface HttpClient { readonly get: (u: string) => Effect.Effect<string, HttpErr> }
const HttpClient = Context.GenericTag<HttpClient>("app/HttpClient");

const HttpClientLive = Layer.succeed(HttpClient, {
  get: (u) => Effect.tryPromise({
    try: () => fetch(u).then((r) => r.text()),
    catch: (c) => new HttpErr({ cause: c }),
  }),
});

const policy = Schedule.intersect(
  Schedule.exponential(Duration.millis(100)),
  Schedule.recurs(3),
);

const program = Effect.gen(function* () {
  const http = yield* HttpClient;
  return yield* Effect.retry(http.get("https://example.com"), policy);
});

void Effect.provide(program, HttpClientLive);
```
